reviewText:
This game is a prequel of the first game in the Blackwell series, and is fairly similar to it. The plot is similar, some characters are the same, and the gameplay in general is that of a nicely crafted adventure game. There are however some differences also, such as different art style, different dynamic between characters, and some adjustments to gameplay from the first game.

Without going into spoilers too much, here are pros and cons, according to me.

PROS:
Low price;
Really good story, better than the first game, in my opinion;
Interesting dialogue;
Better puzzles, didn't get stuck as much as the first one;

CONS:
Absolutely completely remarkably poor choice of achievements, some are impossible to find without the guide, some are downright annoying. Sure some are OK, but that is not an excuse for the two smoking achievements that have no purpose and do nothing except irritate the player who has to replay the game just because the girl smoked and extra smoke or did not smoke enough.
Less likable art style, art feels rushed and, well, amateurish. No character portraits, which is disappointing, especially compared to the first game.
Needed to play the game twice to get the commentary achievement, and then another time to get the smoking achievements (the girl smokes more when Joey is active and you are listening to the commentary). This is 3 times I had to play a game that does not change one bit from playthrough to playthrough. I find this completely unacceptable and poor game design (believe it or not, achievements are part of game design, and if you choose to include them, make sure they add to the game and not subtract from it).
I feel the need to type things in manually demands more from player, as in have a piece of paper and a pen on them when playing. I found this to be somewhat annoying, A game should not need to do that to a player.

Overall, I can only recommend this game because of the good story and puzzles.
